<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="backlog-grooming-roadmapping">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>sdd</group>
    <domain>sdd-planning</domain>
    <summary>Structured process for prioritizing backlogs using RICE scoring and MoSCoW categorization, translating top-priority items into Now/Next/Later roadmaps with theme-based or time-based structure.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>backlog</tag>
      <tag>grooming</tag>
      <tag>roadmap</tag>
      <tag>prioritization</tag>
      <tag>rice-scoring</tag>
    </tags>
    <category>planning</category>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-25</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Backlog Grooming and Roadmapping</title>
    <summary>A structured process for prioritizing backlogs using RICE scoring and MoSCoW categorization, translating the top-priority items into a Now/Next/Later roadmap. The grooming loop runs weekly: triage new ideas, re-score top 20, refine upcoming items, archive stale entries. Roadmaps are theme-based for solo projects and time-based for teams with committed delivery windows.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Projects lose direction when feature requests accumulate without systematic triage. Unscored backlogs cause teams to default to recency bias or vocal stakeholder pressure rather than impact-adjusted effort. RICE scoring (Reach × Impact × Confidence / Effort) gives a reproducible ranking signal; combining it with MoSCoW classification ensures the Must bucket never exceeds 60% of scope, which is the primary driver of missed milestones.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Sprint kickoff: need to pick top N items from backlog for next cycle.</item>
        <item>Quarterly planning: produce a theme-based roadmap from raw backlog data.</item>
        <item>Backlog has grown past 20 unscored items.</item>
        <item>Product review: prioritize incoming requests from users or stakeholders.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Single-task execution sessions where direction is already clear.</item>
        <item>Greenfield projects with no backlog yet. Use spec-requirements or write the first spec directly.</item>
        <item>When RICE inputs (Reach, Impact, Confidence) are pure guesses with no data. Flag as estimate-needed and do not rank.</item>
        <item>Real-time stakeholder negotiations. Async agent output does not substitute for live discussion.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="backlog-structure">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Maintain backlog in five stages: ideas/ (raw, not yet validated), validated/ (aligned with vision, feasibility checked), specified/ (has spec.md), designed/ (has design.md), ready/ (has implementation plan and tasks). Only score validated/ items. Ideas/ are unscored.</statement>
        <rationale>Scoring unvalidated ideas wastes effort on work that may be dropped. The stage gates ensure agent RICE scoring operates on items with sufficient information to produce meaningful numbers.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="weekly-grooming-process">
      <p>Four parts, run weekly in 30-60 minutes:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Part 1 (10 min): Review new ideas. Assess alignment with vision, move to validated/ or drop.</item>
        <item>Part 2 (20 min): Re-score top 20 backlog items with latest data, reorder by priority.</item>
        <item>Part 3 (20 min): Refine upcoming items. Add detail, clarify acceptance criteria, identify dependencies, break into tasks if needed.</item>
        <item>Part 4 (10 min): Archive old items, remove duplicates, update estimates, flag blockers.</item>
      </list>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Never let the backlog exceed 40 unscored items. Schedule agent-assisted triage when it crosses 20 validated items without RICE scores.</statement>
        <rationale>Unscored backlogs default to recency or vocal stakeholder bias, not impact-adjusted effort. An agent can score 20-40 items in one pass given real data inputs.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="rice-scoring">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>RICE Score = (Reach × Impact × Confidence) / Effort. Reach: 1-10 (users affected). Impact: 0.25/0.5/1/2/3 (per user). Confidence: 50%/80%/100%. Effort: person-months (0.5/1/2/3/6+). Flag any item lacking real data for Reach or Impact as estimate-needed.</statement>
        <rationale>Agent-generated RICE numbers are hallucinated if inputs are not grounded in real data. Flagging estimate-needed items prevents false ranking precision.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="RICE scoring examples">
        <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[
Feature: Add social login (Google, GitHub)
Reach: 8 (80% of users would use it)
Impact: 1 (medium — convenience feature)
Confidence: 80% (competitor data available)
Effort: 1 (1 person-month)
RICE Score: (8 × 1 × 0.8) / 1 = 6.4

Feature: Add dark mode
Reach: 3 (30% of users requested)
Impact: 0.5 (cosmetic improvement)
Confidence: 100% (clear requirement)
Effort: 0.5 (~2 weeks)
RICE Score: (3 × 0.5 × 1.0) / 0.5 = 3.0

Decision: Social login (6.4) > Dark mode (3.0). Do social login first.
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="moscow-allocation">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Must = ~60% of scope, Should = ~20%, Could = ~20%. Document Won't items explicitly with a reason. If Must exceeds 60%, reprioritize. Everything being Must means nothing is prioritized.</statement>
        <rationale>All-Must priority is the most common cause of missed milestones. The 60/20/20 split forces prioritization decisions that surface trade-offs before implementation begins.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agents marking everything as Must priority.</description>
        <reason>Violates MoSCoW allocation and creates scope overrun risk. Enforce: Must cannot exceed 60% in the prompt explicitly.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="roadmap-format-selection">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use theme-based roadmaps for solo projects. Use time-based roadmaps for teams with committed delivery windows and external stakeholders. Never use both simultaneously in the same document.</statement>
        <rationale>Theme-based roadmaps are more stable. Themes do not shift when quarters slip. Time-based roadmaps create false commitment pressure that causes rushed decisions when dates approach.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="now-next-later-structure">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Now items must have a target milestone and status (On Track / At Risk / Delayed). Next items must have a confidence level (High/Medium/Low). Later items carry only thematic groupings. No dates, no status.</statement>
        <rationale>Precision decreases with planning horizon. Forcing concrete dates on Later items creates false precision for work that will change as earlier work lands and requirements evolve.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Re-run grooming every 4-6 weeks, not once per quarter. Later items drift. Roadmaps not refreshed regularly become obstacles rather than guides.</statement>
        <rationale>Quarterly roadmap reviews are too infrequent for fast-moving projects. Items in Later bucket will have changed priority. Failing to update the roadmap means the team is working against stale priorities.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <reference path="templates/roadmap.md">Roadmap skeleton with Now/Next/Later sections, Not Planned list, Dependencies, Change Log.</reference>
    </section>
    <section name="wont-do-list">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Document items explicitly excluded from the roadmap with a reason. A Won't do list prevents repeated re-prioritization of the same rejected idea.</statement>
        <rationale>Without an explicit exclusion list, rejected ideas re-enter grooming sessions on each cycle. Documenting why they were rejected short-circuits the debate.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="antipatterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Roadmap treated as a commitment: We promised Q2 for this feature.</description>
        <reason>Roadmap is a plan, not a promise. It must be updated as learning occurs. Treating it as a commitment prevents honest updates when circumstances change.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Too many P0/Must items (more than 3 simultaneous most important features).</description>
        <reason>If everything is most important, nothing is. Forces hard prioritization decisions before the roadmap is published.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Grooming session run as a status update meeting.</description>
        <reason>Grooming focuses on prioritization, not updates. Status belongs in stand-up or async reports. Combining them dilutes both.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>A subagent reads the backlog directory (.aidocs/backlog/), applies RICE scoring to each item using provided data points, and outputs a ranked priority list with MoSCoW classification. A second pass generates a Now/Next/Later roadmap grouped by strategic themes. Human reviews and approves before the roadmap is finalized. The faion-sdd-executor-agent can then execute items from the Now bucket sequentially.</p>
      <p>Recommended subagents:</p>
      <list>
        <item>faion-sdd-executor-agent. Executes implementation tasks for items promoted from backlog to in-progress.</item>
        <item>General planning subagent (claude-opus-4-5 or claude-opus-4-7). Strategic roadmap generation, dependency chain analysis.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="prompt-patterns">
      <p>For RICE scoring:</p>
      <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Read all files in .aidocs/backlog/ideas/. For each item, compute RICE score using:
Reach={provided_reach}, Impact={provided_impact}, Confidence={confidence}%, Effort={effort_months}.
Output a ranked table (highest score first) with MoSCoW column.
Flag any item lacking data for Reach or Impact as estimate-needed.
      ]]></code>
      <p>For roadmap generation:</p>
      <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Given the ranked backlog above, group items into a Now/Next/Later roadmap.
Now = Must items scoring greater than 5 RICE. Next = Should items scoring 2-5. Later = rest.
Output roadmap.md following the template in templates.md.
      ]]></code>
    </section>
    <section name="tools-and-services">
      <p>CLI tools for backlog management:</p>
      <list>
        <item>gh (GitHub CLI). Manage GitHub Issues as backlog items, add labels, milestones. Install: brew install gh. Docs: https://cli.github.com</item>
        <item>jq. Parse/filter JSON from PM APIs. Install: apt install jq. Docs: https://stedolan.github.io/jq/</item>
        <item>roadmap-cli (OSS). Generate terminal roadmap charts from JSON. Install: npm i -g roadmap-cli. Docs: https://github.com/nickvdyck/roadmap</item>
        <item>linear CLI. Query/update Linear issues from shell. Install: npm i -g @linear/sdk. Docs: https://developers.linear.app/docs/sdk/getting-started</item>
      </list>
      <p>Storage platforms:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Linear. Best API for agent-driven backlog reads; webhooks for triggers.</item>
        <item>GitHub Projects. Native if codebase is on GitHub; GraphQL API available.</item>
        <item>Productboard. Good for input aggregation; agents can read feature requests.</item>
        <item>Notion. Flexible but unstructured; agent must parse free-form content.</item>
        <item>Trello. Simple REST API for kanban-style backlog.</item>
        <item>Coda. Tables work well for RICE scoring sheets.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Keep RICE scores in the backlog item file, not in a separate spreadsheet. Agents need single-file context.</item>
        <item>Add a RICE Score section to every .aidocs/backlog/*/ item as part of grooming.</item>
        <item>Mark roadmap items as Confidence: High/Medium/Low. Agents must propagate uncertainty, not hide it.</item>
        <item>Never let the backlog exceed 40 unscored items; schedule agent-assisted triage when it crosses 20.</item>
        <item>Use theme-based roadmaps (not time-based) for solo projects. Quarters shift, themes don't.</item>
        <item>Document Won't do items explicitly; prevents repeated re-prioritization of the same rejected idea.</item>
        <item>Separate ideas/ from validated/ in .aidocs/backlog/; agents only score validated items.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <list>
        <item>Agent RICE scores are hallucinated if Reach/Impact inputs are not grounded in real data. Always supply numbers in the prompt.</item>
        <item>Roadmap Later bucket items will drift; re-run grooming every 4-6 weeks, not once per quarter.</item>
        <item>Agents tend to mark everything Must. Enforce: Must less than or equal to 60% of scope rule in the prompt explicitly.</item>
        <item>Human-in-loop checkpoint required before promoting any item from backlog to spec phase.</item>
        <item>Token budget: full backlog read + roadmap write for 40 items = 30-50k tokens; use Sonnet, not Haiku.</item>
        <item>If backlog items lack descriptions, agent output will be generic; enforce item template before grooming.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/backlog-item.md" purpose="Backlog item skeleton with RICE score table, MoSCoW checkboxes, dependencies, and next steps."/>
      <template path="templates/grooming-session.md" purpose="Grooming session record: ideas reviewed, priority changes, items refined, archived, next sprint candidates."/>
      <template path="templates/roadmap.md" purpose="Product roadmap skeleton with Now/Next/Later sections, Not Planned list, dependencies, change log."/>
      <template path="templates/gh-backlog-export.sh" purpose="Bash script: exports GitHub Issues labeled backlog to RICE-ready CSV using gh CLI and jq."/>
    </templates>
